In other words, it's one of the most brilliant pieces of cinematic work I've ever seen.

POSSIBLE VERY LIGHT, MOSTLY ARBITRARY SPOILERS AHEAD

Charlie Kaufman continues to prove why he's the best at what he does, which is soaking you head-to-toe with existential dread and philosophy, so much so that your brain hurts along with your soul. His direction is fantastic here, every shot and camera movement serves a purpose, even if it's not apparent at first glance. The script is amazing; it provides barely any answers to the various questions it poses, but the questions it poses can't be answered anyway. Kaufman's command of the story and its eccentric, offbeat characters is refreshingly focused and deliberate, with every scene, every line of dialogue that seems like a filler actually serving a larger purpose. The tone is handled very well too. With a story like this, the execution of its disparate blend of subjects, tones, and genres can easily be fumbled and made awkward, but Kaufman is able to effortlessly combine all of the jarring aspects of the story into one cohesive whole.

On a filmmaking level, it is literally flawless. The cinematography is simple yet striking, with the most seemingly arbitrary of images providing some of the biggest impacts this film has to offer. The score is minimalist in nature for most of the runtime, but is still lovely to hear whenever it does pop up. And when the music becomes an important part of the film later on, it's absolutely astounding (the entire final act of the film is truly something to behold). The sets and costumes were all really great and helped create the film's singular, unique atmosphere. One thing that I was surprised by how good it was was the makeup. I didn't expect it to play that much into the story, but the makeup work throughout is pretty phenomenal.

Last but DEFINITELY not least, the performances of it's immensely talented cast are unforgettable.

